  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 21.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And I have set there a place for the ark, wherein is the covenant of the Lord",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [Hence its name, \"the ark of the covenant\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 34:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 9:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ")] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "which he made with our forefathers",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "when he brought them out of the land of Egypt",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [vers. 9, 16]. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "SECTION II.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - The Prayer. The prayer of dedication, properly so called, now begins. This solemn and beautiful composition was probably copied by our author from the \"Book of the Acts of Solomon\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 11:41",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), possibly from the \"Book of Nathan the prophet\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 9:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). It was evidently committed to writing beforehand, and would, no doubt, as a matter of course, be religiously preserved. The later criticism objects to its authenticity that the many references to the Pentateuch (compare ver. 12 with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 19:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ver. 31 with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 22:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 5:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ver. 33 with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 26:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 28:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ver. 36 with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 26:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ver. 50 with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 26:40, 42",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ver. 51 with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.) prove it to be of a later date. Ewald assigns it to the  ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "date",
        "text": "seventh century B.C.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; but this is simply to beg the question of the date of the Pentateuch. It is obviously open to reply that these references only prove that the king was acquainted, as he was bound to be (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 17:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), with the words of the law. It divides itself into three parts. The first (vers. 22-30) is general; the second (vers. 31-53) consists of seven special petitions; the last (vers. 50-53) consists of a general conclusion and appeal to God's covenant mercy. 1 Kings 8:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "\"And Jehovah has set up His word.\" וגו ויּקם supplies the explanation of בידו מלּא (hath fulfilled with his hand) in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 8:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". God had caused Solomon to take possession of the throne of David; and Solomon had built the temple and prepared a place there for the ark of the covenant. The ark is thereby declared to be the kernel and star of the temple, because it was the throne of the glory of God. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]